Part 3

The boy arrived at three in the afternoon, when the shadows of the neem trees had stretched across the courtyard well.

He was carrying a blue canvas bag with a rusted zip that didn't go all the way to the end.

His shoes were cheap black canvas, the soles worn thin, a line of grey station dust outlining the toes.

He stood near the swollen wooden door.

He didn't knock.

He simply stood, his hands holding the straps of the bag, looking at the nameplate *Sen family* with the quiet concentration of a passenger checking a ticket.

Ananya saw him first from her table.

She stood up, holding her pen.

"You are Rehman?"

The boy nodded. He had a slight Odia accent in his voice.

"My mother sent me," he said.

Vikram came out of the back room, carrying a bucket of lime wash he'd been using to repair the kitchen wall.

His hands were white with the wash, a splash of it dried near his left temple.

He set the bucket down.

The boy saw him.

He didn't fold his hands immediately. He looked at Vikram's face, his eyes moving slowly from the white splash on the temple to the faded shirt, then down to his calloused hands.

Then he bowed, his hands folding near his chest.

"Vikram uncle?"

"Yes," Vikram said.

"I am Rehman."

Vikram looked at the boy's eyes.

They were large, dark, the shape of the lids identical to the ones that had watched him fact-check quotes in the Salt Lake office ten years ago.

But they had none of her restlessness. They were still.

"Your train was on time?" Vikram asked.

"Two hours late at Howrah," the boy said. "I took the bus to Bagbazar crossing. The conductor showed the lane."

Sarita came out, leaning on her bamboo cane.

She looked at the canvas bag.

"Have you eaten?"

"No, didi," the boy said.

"Ramu's nephew is in the kitchen. Tell him to give the dal. The rice is cold, but it works."

She looked at Vikram.

"He can sleep in the corner of the side hall. Ramesh's old bed is empty since he went to the hospital."

Rehman looked at the courtyard tap.

"I will wash the face first," he said.

---

He washed at the tap.

He drew the water with one hand, his canvas bag kept carefully on the stone ledge near Ananya's table.

Vikram watched him from the verandah.

The boy's neck was thin, the vertebrae standing out under the collar of his faded blue shirt as he bent over the tap.

He washed twice, using a small piece of red soap he'd brought from his bag.

It was the cheap, local soap sold at Cuttack shops.

He wiped his face with a small green towel.

"Where is the work, uncle?" he asked, coming back to the steps.

"The work is everywhere," Vikram said. "Today, we are whitewashing the kitchen. Tomorrow, the medicine delivery arrives."

"I can do the whitewash," the boy said.

He picked up the spare brush near the bucket.

He didn't ask how to hold it. He didn't ask where to start.

He simply went to the kitchen door, looked at the grey patch on the wall where the plaster had been repaired, and began to paint.

His strokes were slow, slightly uneven, but he didn't stop until the grey was covered in clean, flat white.

Vikram stood beside him.

He took the second brush.

For one hour, they painted the wall together, the smell of fresh lime and damp brick rising between them in the small kitchen.

Outside, the afternoon faded.

The shadow of the neem trees covered the well.

Ananya sat at her table, her pen moving regularly as she entered the evening medicines in the green cloth ledger.

At five, Ramu's nephew brought the kettle.

Red tea.

Shankar's jaggery had gone, but Sarita had bought a small cone of palm sugar from the market.

They sat on the verandah steps.

Three mismatched glasses.

"It is good tea," Rehman said, blowing on the hot glass.

"It is cheap," Sarita said, sitting near Ananya. "But it keeps us warm."

The boy drank.

He looked at the neem trees, at the old marble nameplate, at the white wall he had painted.

"My mother told me," Rehman said, his voice quiet. "She said you were a tycoon once."

Vikram looked at his glass.

The red tea was hot, the palm sugar sweet and dark.

"She was mistaken," Vikram said.

"I was never a tycoon."

The boy smiled.

A small, quiet smile that had nothing of the boardroom in it, and nothing of Cuttack.

"I know," Rehman said.

"The tycoon would never have painted the kitchen."

Vikram drank his tea.

The Bagbazar tap water was heavy, but the red tea tasted of the fresh lime on his brush and the neem leaves in the wind.

He looked at the yellow envelope sitting on the study table inside.

The envelope was closed.

The boy was here.

And as the night settled over the Sen family house, the red tea in his hand was the ultimate thing.

[End of Part 3]
